body:
I'm not sure if this is an error, but it _feels_ wrong to me. It's maybe related to #15144. Here's the code:

``` rust
trait Bar<'a> {
    fn bar(self) -> &'a str;
}

impl Bar<'static> for &'static str {
    fn bar(self) -> &'static str {
        self
    }
}

impl<'a> Bar<'a> for &'a String {
    fn bar(self) -> &'a str {
        self.as_str()
    }
}

fn foo<'a, T, U>(x: T, y: U) -> &'a str
    where T: Bar<'a>,
          U: Bar<'a>
{
    let x = x.bar();
    let y = y.bar();
    if x < y {
        x
    } else {
        y
    }
}

fn main() {
    let s = String::from("Goodbye");
    let x = foo("Hello", &s);
    println!("{}", x);
}
```

Here's the compile-time error:

```
src/main.rs:32:27: 32:28 error: `s` does not live long enough
src/main.rs:32     let x = foo("Hello", &s);
                                         ^
note: reference must be valid for the static lifetime...
src/main.rs:31:37: 34:2 note: ...but borrowed value is only valid for the block suffix following statement 0 at 31:36
src/main.rs:31     let s = String::from("Goodbye");
src/main.rs:32     let x = foo("Hello", &s);
src/main.rs:33     println!("{}", x);
src/main.rs:34 }
```

It seems to me that, because the `T` type parameter to `foo` evaluates to `Bar<'static>` and `U` evaluates to `Bar<'lifetime_of_s_in_main>`, `foo` should evaluate its `'a` lifetime to be `'lifetime_of_s_in_main`, not `'static`.
